  "prompt": "What is Electromagnetic spectrum?",
  "response": "The **electromagnetic spectrum** is the range of all types of **electromagnetic radiation**. Electromagnetic radiation consists of waves of electric and magnetic energy oscillating together, traveling through space at the speed of light (approximately \\( 3 \\times 10^8 \\) meters per second). The electromagnetic spectrum is divided into different regions based on the wavelength and frequency of the waves.\n\n### Key Regions of the Electromagnetic Spectrum (from longest wavelength to shortest):\n1. **Radio Waves**:\n   - Longest wavelength, lowest frequency.\n   - Used in communication (radio, television, mobile phones).\n\n2. **Microwaves**:\n   - Shorter than radio waves.\n   - Used in microwave ovens, radar, and satellite communication.\n\n3. **Infrared (IR) Radiation**:\n   - Longer than visible light.\n   - Produced by heat; used in remote controls, thermal imaging, and night vision.\n\n4. **Visible Light**:\n   - The portion of the spectrum detectable by the human eye.\n   - Ranges from red (longest wavelength) to violet (shortest wavelength).\n\n5. **Ultraviolet (UV) Radiation**:\n   - Shorter than visible light.\n   - Can cause sunburn; used in sterilization and fluorescent lights.\n\n6. **X-rays**:\n   - Very short wavelength, high energy.\n   - Used in medical imaging and security scanning.\n\n7. **Gamma Rays**:\n   - Shortest wavelength, highest frequency and energy.\n   - Produced by radioactive decay and nuclear reactions; used in cancer treatment and astronomical observation.\n\n### Properties:\n- **Wavelength**: The distance between successive peaks (or troughs) of a wave.\n- **Frequency**: The number of wave cycles per second (measured in Hertz, Hz).\n- **Energy**: Higher frequency waves have more energy (e.g., gamma rays) than lower frequency waves (e.g., radio waves).\n\nAll electromagnetic waves travel at the same speed in a vacuum, but their wavelengths and frequencies vary. The electromagnetic spectrum is a fundamental concept in physics, astronomy, communications, and many other fields.",
